07066nam a22010335i 9783110918076DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20112005gw     fo  d z      ger d  a(OCoLC)1013949702  a97831109180767 a10.1515/97831109180762doi  a(DE-B1597)56582  a(OCoLC)840445275  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 ager  agwcDE 4aPT405b.M984 2005 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.915222  aEC 26002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/20496:00aMythenkorrekturen :bZu einer paradoxalen Form der Mythenrezeption /chrsg. von Bernd Seidensticker, Martin Vöhler. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2011] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (486 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aspectrum Literaturwissenschaft / spectrum Literature : Komparatistische Studien / Comparative Studies ,x1860-210X ;v30 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDer Begriff ‚Mythenkorrektur‘ bezeichnet ein literarisches Verfahren, das den Mythos nicht fortschreibt, sondern überraschende Eingriffe an seinem eigentlich geschützten Kern vornimmt: Schweigende Sirenen oder ein glücklicher Sisyphos. Form und Gestaltungen solcher Korrekturen untersucht der vorliegende Band erstmals systematisch an Beispielen von der Antike bis zur Literatur der Gegenwart.  aThe concept of corrected myths is not (yet) established in literary studies. This volume introduces this concept and demonstrates its power using exemplary interpretations. It is the case that in numerous literary works, knowledge of a conventional mythical connection is assumed, but then, at a particular point, the traditional narrative is negated – Candaule’s wife was not beautiful, the Sirens did not sing, Oedipus was not surprised by the news (Brecht) etc. The corrections always occur at a significant point, so that the intervention casts a new light on well-known narratives, but in principle does not affect the core of the myth. The present volume examines the forms and functions of such corrected myths. For this, relevant works of European literature are studied and their interpretation related with considerations of Antique myths, Christian corrections of myths, new mythology and the correction of myths from existentialism to post-modernism. The spectrum of texts examined is kept as wide as possible to allow for a broad conception of correction. The texts include those from authors such as Heiner Müller, Thomas Brasch, Christa Wolf und Volker Braun and by Shakespeare, Goethe and Kleist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxClassical influences. 0aMythology, Classical, in literature. 4aAntikenrezeption /i.d. Literatur. 4aEuropa /Literatur, Literaturgeschichte. 4aMythologie /i.d. Literatur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAurnhammer, Achim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBennholdt-Thomsen, Anke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirkenhauer, Theresia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDangel-Pelloquin, Elsbeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDehrmann, Mark-Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhlers, Widu-Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmerich, Wolfgang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmmerich, Wolfgang.1 aFebel, Gisela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreiner, Bernhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHahn, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonold, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHühn